™—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@32ad4622fe06004acc11ec8f3544dddf9941616d283bb90396c463c0679f0461іtitle: Nushell 0.34‘¬Nushell 0.34Ъ™



Nushell, or Nu for short, is a new shell that takes a modern, structured approach to your commandline. It works seamlessly with the data from your filesystem, operating system, and a growing number of file formats to make it easy to build powerful commandline pipelines.
Today, we're releasing 0.34 of Nu. This release is the first to support dataframes and also includes a set of usability improvements.
’ђђЪРTitle: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: Nushell 0.34
Content:




Nushell, or Nu for short, is a new shell that takes a modern, structured approach to your commandline. It works seamlessly with the data from your filesystem, operating system, and a growing number of file formats to make it easy to build powerful commandline pipelines.
Today, we're releasing 0.34 of Nu. This release is the first to support dataframes and also includes a set of usability improvements.
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@e6df89f3bde0646dca79cd3ef7322e4faf19b3a8d739d44a4c101548c6ed1958іtitle: Nushell 0.34‘ЇWhere to get itЪiNu 0.34 is available as 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.34.0] pre-built binaries
 or from 
[link: https://crates.io/crates/nu] crates.io
. If you have Rust installed you can install it using 
``cargo install nu``
.
If you want all the goodies, you can install 
``cargo install nu --features=extra``
.
If you'd like to try the experimental paging feature in this release, you can install with 
``cargo install nu --features=table-pager``
.
As part of this release, we also publish a set of plugins you can install and use with Nu. To install, use 
``cargo install nu_plugin_<plugin name>``
.
’ђђЪЈTitle: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: Where to get it
Content:
Nu 0.34 is available as 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.34.0] pre-built binaries
 or from 
[link: https://crates.io/crates/nu] crates.io
. If you have Rust installed you can install it using 
``cargo install nu``
.
If you want all the goodies, you can install 
``cargo install nu --features=extra``
.
If you'd like to try the experimental paging feature in this release, you can install with 
``cargo install nu --features=table-pager``
.
As part of this release, we also publish a set of plugins you can install and use with Nu. To install, use 
``cargo install nu_plugin_<plugin name>``
.
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@09af31d4d54fc6068fc5454b14bfe47d77dfdc80f374e66d3946950cf12ec9d3іtitle: Nushell 0.34‘№Dataframes (elferherrera)ЪJWith 0.34, we've introduced a new family of commands to work with dataframes. Dataframes are an efficient way of working with large datasets by storing data as columns and offering a set of operations over them.
To create a dataframe, you can use the 
``dataframe open``
 command and pass it a source file to load. This command currently supports CSV and parquet files.
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> let df = (dataframe open .\Data7602DescendingYearOrder.csv)

```
Once loaded, there are a variety of commands you can use to interact with the dataframe (you can get the full list with 
``dataframe --help``
). For example, to see the first few rows of the dataframe we just loaded, we can use 
``dataframe first``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> $df | dataframe first

в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 # в”‚ anzsic06 в”‚  Area   в”‚ year в”‚ geo_count в”‚ ec_count
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 0 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100100 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        96 в”‚      130
 1 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100200 в”‚ 2000 в”‚       198 в”‚      110
 2 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100300 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        42 в”‚       25
 3 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100400 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        66 в”‚       40
 4 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100500 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        63 в”‚       40
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
Where dataframes really shine is their performance.
For example, the above dataset is 5 columns and ~5.5 million rows of data. We're able to process group it by the year column, sum the results, and display it to the user in 557ms:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
# process.nu
let df = (dataframe open Data7602DescendingYearOrder.csv)
let res = ($df | dataframe group-by year | dataframe aggregate sum | dataframe select geo_count)
$res

```
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> benchmark {source process.nu}

в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 # в”‚     real time
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 0 в”‚ 557ms 658us 500ns
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
By comparison, here's the same example in pandas:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv("Data7602DescendingYearOrder.csv")
res = df.groupby("year")["geo_count"].sum()
print(res)

```
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> benchmark {python .\load.py}

в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 # в”‚       real time
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 0 в”‚ 1sec 966ms 954us 800ns
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
System Details: The benchmarks presented in this section were run using a machine with a processor Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-10710U (CPU @1.10GHz 1.61 GHz) and 16 gb of RAM.
While these results are still early, we're excited to see what can be possible using Nushell for processing large datasets.
You can learn more about dataframes, including many examples and a much more in-depth explanation, by reading the new 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/book/dataframes.html] dataframes chapter of the Nushell book
.
Note: while all the dataframe functionality is currently grouped behind the 
``dataframe``
 top-level command, we hope to extend support for dataframes to other common Nushell commands.
’ђђЪЋTitle: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: Dataframes (elferherrera)
Content:
With 0.34, we've introduced a new family of commands to work with dataframes. Dataframes are an efficient way of working with large datasets by storing data as columns and offering a set of operations over them.
To create a dataframe, you can use the 
``dataframe open``
 command and pass it a source file to load. This command currently supports CSV and parquet files.
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> let df = (dataframe open .\Data7602DescendingYearOrder.csv)

```
Once loaded, there are a variety of commands you can use to interact with the dataframe (you can get the full list with 
``dataframe --help``
). For example, to see the first few rows of the dataframe we just loaded, we can use 
``dataframe first``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> $df | dataframe first

в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 # в”‚ anzsic06 в”‚  Area   в”‚ year в”‚ geo_count в”‚ ec_count
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 0 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100100 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        96 в”‚      130
 1 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100200 в”‚ 2000 в”‚       198 в”‚      110
 2 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100300 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        42 в”‚       25
 3 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100400 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        66 в”‚       40
 4 в”‚ A        в”‚ A100500 в”‚ 2000 в”‚        63 в”‚       40
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
Where dataframes really shine is their performance.
For example, the above dataset is 5 columns and ~5.5 million rows of data. We're able to process group it by the year column, sum the results, and display it to the user in 557ms:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
# process.nu
let df = (dataframe open Data7602DescendingYearOrder.csv)
let res = ($df | dataframe group-by year | dataframe aggregate sum | dataframe select geo_count)
$res

```
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> benchmark {source process.nu}

в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 # в”‚     real time
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 0 в”‚ 557ms 658us 500ns
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
By comparison, here's the same example in pandas:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv("Data7602DescendingYearOrder.csv")
res = df.groupby("year")["geo_count"].sum()
print(res)

```
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> benchmark {python .\load.py}

в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 # в”‚       real time
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
 0 в”‚ 1sec 966ms 954us 800ns
в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
System Details: The benchmarks presented in this section were run using a machine with a processor Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-10710U (CPU @1.10GHz 1.61 GHz) and 16 gb of RAM.
While these results are still early, we're excited to see what can be possible using Nushell for processing large datasets.
You can learn more about dataframes, including many examples and a much more in-depth explanation, by reading the new 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/book/dataframes.html] dataframes chapter of the Nushell book
.
Note: while all the dataframe functionality is currently grouped behind the 
``dataframe``
 top-level command, we hope to extend support for dataframes to other common Nushell commands.
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@f2b3abd3151e55368e5060037c403d99f3a546acecbe1819f605e66e1f31bce5іtitle: Nushell 0.34‘Щ%Improved multiline support (sophiajt)ЪэWe've extended multiline expression support to more areas. Now, you can span tables over multiple lines more naturally:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
[
  [name, value];
  [foo, 2]
  [bar, 7]
]

```
Subexpression now also span multiple lines. Everything inside of the parentheses are treated as if they were written together:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
(echo foo
| str length)

```
This also gives you a way to split up commands that have many arguments over multiple lines:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
(echo foo
bar)

```
’ђђЪMTitle: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: Improved multiline support (sophiajt)
Content:
We've extended multiline expression support to more areas. Now, you can span tables over multiple lines more naturally:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
[
  [name, value];
  [foo, 2]
  [bar, 7]
]

```
Subexpression now also span multiple lines. Everything inside of the parentheses are treated as if they were written together:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
(echo foo
| str length)

```
This also gives you a way to split up commands that have many arguments over multiple lines:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
(echo foo
bar)

```
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@a8f5bafd2cd90759bcef5405529be8e7ed64fe222ad1885be91a99a050e14c23іtitle: Nushell 0.34‘Щ.Multiple shorthand environment vars (sophiajt)ЩДA long-time shortcoming is now fixed in 0.34. You can now pass multiple environment shorthands to the same command:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> FOO=bar BAR=baz $nu.env.FOO + $nu.env.BAR
barbaz

```
’ђђЪTitle: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: Multiple shorthand environment vars (sophiajt)
Content:
A long-time shortcoming is now fixed in 0.34. You can now pass multiple environment shorthands to the same command:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> FOO=bar BAR=baz $nu.env.FOO + $nu.env.BAR
barbaz

```
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@3a018705be7432f62b8df759c78fb1ae9f33bf0f7bdf19b079d3b8e8976e084aіtitle: Nushell 0.34‘їVariable completions (andrasio)ЪsIn addition to steadily improving the completion engine, we've started adding support for completions for built-in variables.
You can now write 
``$nu.<TAB>``
 to complete into the built-in 
``$nu``
 variable, including completions for 
``$nu.env.S<TAB>``
 for completing into environment variables.
Other variables that are in scope can also have their names completed.
’ђђЪЅTitle: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: Variable completions (andrasio)
Content:
In addition to steadily improving the completion engine, we've started adding support for completions for built-in variables.
You can now write 
``$nu.<TAB>``
 to complete into the built-in 
``$nu``
 variable, including completions for 
``$nu.env.S<TAB>``
 for completing into environment variables.
Other variables that are in scope can also have their names completed.
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@43a2b46bad87d49c6f7834faed22e4dfb001b9eebfa7e7beace490fe5019512dіtitle: Nushell 0.34‘¬New commandsЪdAdded the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3670] ``pathvar``
 command for updating the PATH
 (nathom)
Added a 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3694] ``paste``
 command for pasting from clipboard
 (1ntEgr8)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3720] ``$nu.lang``
 to reflect on the current commands
 (fdncred)
’ђђЪ›Title: title: Nushell 0.34
Path: New commands
Content:
Added the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3670] ``pathvar``
 command for updating the PATH
 (nathom)
Added a 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3694] ``paste``
 command for pasting from clipboard
 (1ntEgr8)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3720] ``$nu.lang``
 to reflect on the current commands
 (fdncred)
—ЩVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.mdЩ@e044046de92ff42b1abce45c913e73d78030699dfc4eed5e159a17c4b67f0149іtitle: Nushell 0.34‘·Additional improvementsЪ…Updated 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3758] ``into binary``
 to be more composable
 (fdncred)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3754] unique option to 
``uniq``
 (mcbattirola)
Removed an 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3751] outdated README note
 (yaymukund)
Added more 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3750] comparison coercions with 
``$nothing``
 (sophiajt)
Updated the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3749] ``version``
 command to output more info
 (fdncred)
Fixed a 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3745] broken unit test
 (fdncred)
Downgraded 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3740] crossterm to fix pager compilation
 (kubouch)
Removed 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3732] unused crate features
 (waywardmonkeys)
Updated a few 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3723] dependencies
 and 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3724] here
 and 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3739] here
 and 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3741] here
 and 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3757] here
 (therealprof, waywardmonkeys)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3722] dataframe take command
 (elferherrera)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3717] script to submit winget package during release
 (TechWatching)
Aligned 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3713] dataframe params to match other Nushell commands
 (elferherrera)
Added the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3712] ansi osc string terminator
 (fdncred)
Removed 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3709] unused dependencies
 and 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3716] also
 (waywardmonkeys, andrasio)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3702] casting operations for Series data
 (elferherrera)
Fixed a 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3697] dataframe series bug with f64
 (elferherrera)
Added 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3696] all-trim option to 
``str trim``
 (palashahuja)
Ported more commands to engine-p 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3690] 1
 and 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3753] 2
 (efx)
Added support for 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3688] arbitrarily nested subcommands
 (sophiajt)
Added support for 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3686] string interpolation when calling externals
 (voanhduy1512)
Made 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3684] URL docs more consistent
 (efx)
Speed up 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3683] dataframe loading
 (elferherrera)
Improved 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3681] parse errors for 
``def``
 (sophiajt)
Updated textview to 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3680] always read its input from the stream
 (sophiajt)
Dataframe aggregation uses 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/3678] simpler column names
